{"title_page": "Giuseppe Di Stefano", "text_new": "{{for|the Italian criminal|Giuseppe De Stefano}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Giuseppe Di Stefano\n| image              = Giuseppe_di_Stefano_singing_opera_by_a_piano.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Giuseppe di Stefano singing opera by a piano in the 1950s.\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1921|07|24}}\n| birth_place        = Motta Sant'Anastasia, Catania, Sicily\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2008|03|03|1921|07|24}}\n| death_place        = Santa Maria Ho\u00e8, Milan, Italy\n| nationality        = Italian\n| other_names        = Pippo\n| occupation         = Opera singer (tenor)\n| years_active       = 1946 - 1992\n| known_for          = Opera\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Giuseppe Di Stefano''' (24 July 1921{{spaced ndash}}3 March 2008) was an Italian operatic [[tenor]] who sang professionally from the mid 1940s until the early 1990s. Called Pippo by both fans and friends, he was known as the \"Golden voice\" or \"The most beautiful voice\", as the true successor of [[Beniamino Gigli]].\n[[Luciano Pavarotti]] said he modeled himself after Di Stefano. In an interview Pavarotti said \"Di Stefano is my idol. ''There'' is a solar voice...It was the most incredible, open voice you could hear. The musicality of di Stefano is as natural and beautiful as the voice is phenomenal\".<ref>''Opera'', January 2002</ref> Di Stefano was also the tenor who most inspired [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]].<ref>{{Citation|last1=Carreras|first1=Jos\u00e8|title=Singing from the Soul|year=1991}} {{Full citation needed|date=January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2015}}\nGiuseppe Di Stefano was born in [[Motta Sant'Anastasia]], a village near [[Catania]], Sicily, in 1921.<ref name=twp3mar /> He was the only son of a carabiniere turned cobbler and his dressmaker wife. Di Stefano was educated at a [[Jesuit]] seminary and briefly contemplated entering the priesthood.\n[[File:Below St. Mark's Lion Italian tenor Giuseppe Di Stefano portrayed from below embracing a man wearing a straw hat, in St. Mark Square, Venice 1948..jpg|thumb|Below St. Mark's Lion. Italian tenor Giuseppe Di Stefano portrayed from below embracing a man wearing a straw hat, in St. Mark Square, Venice 1948. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.dk/detail/news-photo/italian-tenor-giuseppe-di-stefano-portrayed-from-below-news-photo/113917378?adppopup=true|title=Website link|last=|first=|date=|website=https://www.gettyimages.dk/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Piazza San Marco]]]]\nAfter serving in the Italian military (and briefly taking lessons from the Swiss tenor [[Hugues Cu\u00e9nod]]), Di Stefano made his operatic debut in 1946 in [[Reggio Emilia]] as Des Grieux in [[Jules Massenet|Massenet]]'s ''[[Manon]]'', the role in which he made his [[La Scala]] debut the following year. He made his New York debut at the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in February 1948 as the Duke of Mantua in [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Rigoletto]]'' <ref>[http://archives.metoperafamily.org/Imgs/DiStefanoDebut.htm Giuseppe Di Stefano \u2013 Metropolitan Opera debut, February 25, 1948], Metropolitan Opera</ref> after singing the role in Riccione with [[Hj\u00f6rdis Schymberg]] in August of the previous year. After his performance in ''[[Manon]]'' a month later, ''[[Musical America]]'' wrote that Di Stefano \"had the rich velvety sound we have seldom heard since the days of [[Beniamino Gigli|Gigli]]\".<ref>''Musical America'' April 1948, p. 44.</ref> \n\nHe went on to perform regularly in New York for many years. In 1957, Di Stefano made his British debut at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] as Nemorino in ''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' and his [[Royal Opera House]], Covent Garden, debut in 1961, as Cavaradossi in ''[[Tosca]]''.\n\nAs a singer, Di Stefano was admired for his excellent diction, unique timbre, passionate delivery and, in particular, for the sweetness of his soft singing. In his [[Metropolitan Opera radio broadcast]] debut in ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'', he attacked the high C forte and then softened to a [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]]. Sir [[Rudolf Bing]] said in his memoirs, \"The most spectacular single moment in my observation year had come when I heard his diminuendo on the high C in \"{{Lang|fr|Salut! demeure}}\" in ''Faust'': I shall never as long as I live forget the beauty of that sound\".<ref>[[Rudolf Bing|Bing, Rudolf]] (1972) ''5000 Nights at the Opera''. Hamish Hamilton, p. 145.</ref>\n\nDuring his years of international celebrity, Di Stefano won a gold Orfeo, an Italian musical award.<ref name=\"carroll\">{{citation|last=Carroll|first=Rory|authorlink=Rory Carroll|title=Opera star critical after attack in Kenya|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 December 2004|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/dec/06/arts.kenya}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953 [[Walter Legge]], leader of [[EMI]]'s classical wing, wanted a tenor to record all the popular Italian operas with [[Maria Callas]], and chose Di Stefano. Among their recording achievements was the famous [[Tosca (Sabata recording)|1953 studio recording]] of ''[[Tosca]]'' under [[Victor de Sabata]], which is considered \"as being one of the great performances in the history of the gramophone\".<ref>Rosenthal, Harold (1973) ''Opera'' Vol. 24 No. 5, p. 438.</ref> The two also performed together on stage frequently, from 1951 in South America to the end of 1957 in ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' at La Scala, the last time the two collaborated in an opera. He sang Alfredo in the famous Visconti production of ''[[La traviata]]'' in 1955 at La Scala, as well as Edgardo to her Lucia under [[Herbert von Karajan]] at La Scala, Berlin and Vienna.  Rudolf Bing of the Metropolitan Opera House lamented Di Stefano's playboy lifestyle, which he felt was the cause of his vocal decline, although Di Stefano himself blamed allergies to synthetic fibres for permanently damaging his vocal cords.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/04/nyregion/04distefano.html|title=Giuseppe di Stefano, a Tenor Whose Career Flamed Out Too Early, Is Dead at 86|last=Kandell|first=Jonathan|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en}}</ref>\n[[File:Giuseppe di Stefano - 1983.jpg|alt=Giuseppe di Stefano in 1983|thumb|299x299px|Giuseppe di Stefano - 1983]]\nIn 1973, Di Stefano and Maria Callas went together for a recital tour that ended in 1974: critics remarked that Maria Callas had lost her voice, but the public reaction was nevertheless enthusiastic everywhere. It was during this period that there were rumors of a brief romantic relationship between the two singers. \nDi Stefano continued to sing successfully and his final operatic role was as the Emperor in ''[[Turandot]]'', in July 1992.\n\nIn November 2004, Di Stefano was critically injured in his home in [[Diani Beach]], Kenya, after a brutal beating by unknown assailants.<ref name=\"twp3mar\">{{cite news|title=Obituaries in the News|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/03/AR2008030302872_pf.html|accessdate=13 April 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=3 March 2008|agency=AP}}</ref><ref name=\"carroll\" /> He was ambushed in his car with his wife, Monika Curth, as they prepared to drive from their villa in Diani, a coastal resort near [[Mombasa]] on the Indian Ocean. The singer was still unconscious a week after the attack and was fed intravenously, and underwent several operations.\n\nAfter two surgeries in Mombasa, Di Stefano was flown to the San Raffaele clinic at Milan in December 2004, where he slipped into a coma.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dick |first=Charles |title=Italian tenor Di Stefano dies aged 86 |publisher=Reuters |date=3 March 2008 |url=http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL03836685.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309205819/http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL03836685.html |archivedate=9 March 2008 }}</ref> Eventually he awakened from coma, but his health never fully improved.<ref name=\"twp3mar\" /> He died in his home in [[Santa Maria Ho\u00e8]], north of Milan, on 3 March 2008 at the age of 86.<ref name=\"twp3mar\" />\n\n==Recordings with Maria Callas==\n[[File:Giuseppe di Stefano and Maria Callas during the recording of Rigoletto in Milan,16th September, 1955.jpg|alt=Dark haired man with braces singing next to a dark haired woman |thumb|Giuseppe di Stefano and Maria Callas during a recording of Rigoletto in Milan on 16th September, 1955.]]\nDi Stefano and Maria Callas recorded many operas together, all of which for [[EMI]]. Together they recorded the following complete operas:\n\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[I puritani]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[Tosca]]'' \u2013 [[Tosca (1953 EMI recording)|1953]]\n*''[[Pagliacci]]'' \u2013 1954\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' \u2013 1955\n*''[[Il trovatore]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[Manon Lescaut (Puccini)|Manon Lescaut]]'' \u2013 1957\n\nA series of duets with Di Stefano and Callas was recorded by the Philips label in the period November\u2013December 1972, with [[Antonio de Almeida (conductor)|Antonio de Almeida]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra]]. These recordings were not published officially, but a 'pirate' version did appear.\n\n==Other recordings==\nDi Stefano also made many other recordings with other wonderful singers, complete [[EMI]] sets of ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' (opposite [[Victoria de los \u00c1ngeles]], 1954) and ''[[La traviata]]'' (with [[Antonietta Stella]] and [[Tito Gobbi]], 1955).\n\nFor English [[Decca Records|Decca]] he recorded ''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' with [[Hilde Gueden]] and [[Fernando Corena]] (1955), ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'' (with [[Zinka Milanov]] and [[Leonard Warren]], 1957), ''[[La forza del destino]]'' (1958) and ''[[Tosca]]'' (with [[Leontyne Price]] and [[Giuseppe Taddei]], [[Herbert von Karajan]] conducting, 1962).\n\nFor [[Casa Ricordi|Ricordi]] (Ricordi MRO 104/105), he made a complete stereo ''Lucia di Lammermoor'' with [[Renata Scotto]], [[Ettore Bastianini]] and [[Ivo Vinco]] in 1958, with [[Nino Sanzogno]] conducting the Orchestra and Chorus of [[La Scala]], Milan.\n\nIn 1995, VAI issued an approved version of ''La boh\u00e8me'', from a 1959 performance in [[New Orleans]], with the tenor starring opposite [[Licia Albanese]], [[Audrey Schuh]], [[Giuseppe Valdengo]] and [[Norman Treigle]]. Additionally, in 1962 the tenor recorded excerpts from [[Jules Massenet|Massenet]]'s ''Manon'', with [[Anna Moffo]], conducted by [[Ren\u00e9 Leibowitz]].\n\nIn 1951, Di Stefano sang in a performance of Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'', at [[Carnegie Hall]], conducted by [[Arturo Toscanini]], the other soloists being [[Herva Nelli]], [[Fedora Barbieri]] and [[Cesare Siepi]]. It was released as a recording by [[RCA]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''The Oxford Dictionary of Opera'', by [[John Warrack]] and Ewan West (1992), 782 pages, {{ISBN|0-19-869164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Giuseppe Di Stefano}}\n* [http://www.operavivra.com/artists/tenors/di-stefano-giuseppe/ Extended biography at Opera Vivr\u00e0]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223203/http://www.giuseppedistefano.it/indexeng.asp Official site] (mostly in Italian)\n* {{IMDb name|0224339}}\n* {{Find a Grave|25177173}}\n* [[Alan Blyth]] [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/comment/story/0,,2261837,00.html Obituary: Opera singer Giuseppe Di Stefano, 1921\u20132008] ''The Guardian'', 3 March 2008\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110831101318/http://historyofthetenor.com/page.php?90 History of the Tenor \u2013 Sound Clips and Narration]\n*{{YouTube|D5FI7IO1u4A|1974 concert with Maria Callas}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Stefano, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Catania]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Giuseppe di Stefano singing opera by a piano.jpg|alt=Giuseppe di Stefano singing opera by a piano|thumb|285x285px|Giuseppe di Stefano singing opera by a piano in the 1950s.]]{{for|the Italian criminal|Giuseppe De Stefano}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n'''Giuseppe Di Stefano''' (24 July 1921{{spaced ndash}}3 March 2008) was an Italian operatic [[tenor]] who sang professionally from the mid 1940s until the early 1990s. Called Pippo by both fans and friends, he was known as the \"Golden voice\" or \"The most beautiful voice\", as the true successor of [[Beniamino Gigli]].\n[[Luciano Pavarotti]] said he modeled himself after Di Stefano. In an interview Pavarotti said \"Di Stefano is my idol. ''There'' is a solar voice...It was the most incredible, open voice you could hear. The musicality of di Stefano is as natural and beautiful as the voice is phenomenal\".<ref>''Opera'', January 2002</ref> Di Stefano was also the tenor who most inspired [[Jos\u00e9 Carreras]].<ref>{{Citation|last1=Carreras|first1=Jos\u00e8|title=Singing from the Soul|year=1991}} {{Full citation needed|date=January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2015}}\nGiuseppe Di Stefano was born in [[Motta Sant'Anastasia]], a village near [[Catania]], Sicily, in 1921.<ref name=twp3mar /> He was the only son of a carabiniere turned cobbler and his dressmaker wife. Di Stefano was educated at a [[Jesuit]] seminary and briefly contemplated entering the priesthood.\n[[File:Below St. Mark's Lion Italian tenor Giuseppe Di Stefano portrayed from below embracing a man wearing a straw hat, in St. Mark Square, Venice 1948..jpg|thumb|Below St. Mark's Lion. Italian tenor Giuseppe Di Stefano portrayed from below embracing a man wearing a straw hat, in St. Mark Square, Venice 1948. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gettyimages.dk/detail/news-photo/italian-tenor-giuseppe-di-stefano-portrayed-from-below-news-photo/113917378?adppopup=true|title=Website link|last=|first=|date=|website=https://www.gettyimages.dk/|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>[[Piazza San Marco]]]]\nAfter serving in the Italian military (and briefly taking lessons from the Swiss tenor [[Hugues Cu\u00e9nod]]), Di Stefano made his operatic debut in 1946 in [[Reggio Emilia]] as Des Grieux in [[Jules Massenet|Massenet]]'s ''[[Manon]]'', the role in which he made his [[La Scala]] debut the following year. He made his New York debut at the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in February 1948 as the Duke of Mantua in [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Rigoletto]]'' <ref>[http://archives.metoperafamily.org/Imgs/DiStefanoDebut.htm Giuseppe Di Stefano \u2013 Metropolitan Opera debut, February 25, 1948], Metropolitan Opera</ref> after singing the role in Riccione with [[Hj\u00f6rdis Schymberg]] in August of the previous year. After his performance in ''[[Manon]]'' a month later, ''[[Musical America]]'' wrote that Di Stefano \"had the rich velvety sound we have seldom heard since the days of [[Beniamino Gigli|Gigli]]\".<ref>''Musical America'' April 1948, p. 44.</ref> \n\nHe went on to perform regularly in New York for many years. In 1957, Di Stefano made his British debut at the [[Edinburgh Festival]] as Nemorino in ''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' and his [[Royal Opera House]], Covent Garden, debut in 1961, as Cavaradossi in ''[[Tosca]]''.\n\nAs a singer, Di Stefano was admired for his excellent diction, unique timbre, passionate delivery and, in particular, for the sweetness of his soft singing. In his [[Metropolitan Opera radio broadcast]] debut in ''[[Faust (opera)|Faust]]'', he attacked the high C forte and then softened to a [[Dynamics (music)|pianissimo]]. Sir [[Rudolf Bing]] said in his memoirs, \"The most spectacular single moment in my observation year had come when I heard his diminuendo on the high C in \"{{Lang|fr|Salut! demeure}}\" in ''Faust'': I shall never as long as I live forget the beauty of that sound\".<ref>[[Rudolf Bing|Bing, Rudolf]] (1972) ''5000 Nights at the Opera''. Hamish Hamilton, p. 145.</ref>\n\nDuring his years of international celebrity, Di Stefano won a gold Orfeo, an Italian musical award.<ref name=\"carroll\">{{citation|last=Carroll|first=Rory|authorlink=Rory Carroll|title=Opera star critical after attack in Kenya|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=6 December 2004|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/dec/06/arts.kenya}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953 [[Walter Legge]], leader of [[EMI]]'s classical wing, wanted a tenor to record all the popular Italian operas with [[Maria Callas]], and chose Di Stefano. Among their recording achievements was the famous [[Tosca (Sabata recording)|1953 studio recording]] of ''[[Tosca]]'' under [[Victor de Sabata]], which is considered \"as being one of the great performances in the history of the gramophone\".<ref>Rosenthal, Harold (1973) ''Opera'' Vol. 24 No. 5, p. 438.</ref> The two also performed together on stage frequently, from 1951 in South America to the end of 1957 in ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' at La Scala, the last time the two collaborated in an opera. He sang Alfredo in the famous Visconti production of ''[[La traviata]]'' in 1955 at La Scala, as well as Edgardo to her Lucia under [[Herbert von Karajan]] at La Scala, Berlin and Vienna.  Rudolf Bing of the Metropolitan Opera House lamented Di Stefano's playboy lifestyle, which he felt was the cause of his vocal decline, although Di Stefano himself blamed allergies to synthetic fibres for permanently damaging his vocal cords.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/04/nyregion/04distefano.html|title=Giuseppe di Stefano, a Tenor Whose Career Flamed Out Too Early, Is Dead at 86|last=Kandell|first=Jonathan|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Di Stefano and Maria Callas went together for a recital tour that ended in 1974: critics remarked that Maria Callas had lost her voice, but the public reaction was nevertheless enthusiastic everywhere. It was during this period that there were rumors of a brief romantic relationship between the two singers. \nDi Stefano continued to sing successfully and his final operatic role was as the Emperor in ''[[Turandot]]'', in July 1992.\n\nIn November 2004, Di Stefano was critically injured in his home in [[Diani Beach]], Kenya, after a brutal beating by unknown assailants.<ref name=\"twp3mar\">{{cite news|title=Obituaries in the News|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/03/AR2008030302872_pf.html|accessdate=13 April 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=3 March 2008|agency=AP}}</ref><ref name=\"carroll\" /> He was ambushed in his car with his wife, Monika Curth, as they prepared to drive from their villa in Diani, a coastal resort near [[Mombasa]] on the Indian Ocean. The singer was still unconscious a week after the attack and was fed intravenously, and underwent several operations.\n\nAfter two surgeries in Mombasa, Di Stefano was flown to the San Raffaele clinic at Milan in December 2004, where he slipped into a coma.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dick |first=Charles |title=Italian tenor Di Stefano dies aged 86 |publisher=Reuters |date=3 March 2008 |url=http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL03836685.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309205819/http://africa.reuters.com/wire/news/usnL03836685.html |archivedate=9 March 2008 }}</ref> Eventually he awakened from coma, but his health never fully improved.<ref name=\"twp3mar\" /> He died in his home in [[Santa Maria Ho\u00e8]], north of Milan, on 3 March 2008 at the age of 86.<ref name=\"twp3mar\" />\n\n==Recordings with Maria Callas==\n[[File:Giuseppe di Stefano and Maria Callas during the recording of Rigoletto in Milan,16th September, 1955.jpg|alt=Dark haired man with braces singing next to a dark haired woman |thumb|Giuseppe di Stefano and Maria Callas during a recording of Rigoletto in Milan on 16th September, 1955.]]\nDi Stefano and Maria Callas recorded many operas together, all of which for [[EMI]]. Together they recorded the following complete operas:\n\n*''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[I puritani]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[Cavalleria rusticana]]'' \u2013 1953\n*''[[Tosca]]'' \u2013 [[Tosca (1953 EMI recording)|1953]]\n*''[[Pagliacci]]'' \u2013 1954\n*''[[Rigoletto]]'' \u2013 1955\n*''[[Il trovatore]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[La boh\u00e8me]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' \u2013 1956\n*''[[Manon Lescaut (Puccini)|Manon Lescaut]]'' \u2013 1957\n\nA series of duets with Di Stefano and Callas was recorded by the Philips label in the period November\u2013December 1972, with [[Antonio de Almeida (conductor)|Antonio de Almeida]] conducting the [[London Symphony Orchestra]]. These recordings were not published officially, but a 'pirate' version did appear.\n\n==Other recordings==\nDi Stefano also made many other recordings with other wonderful singers, complete [[EMI]] sets of ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' (opposite [[Victoria de los \u00c1ngeles]], 1954) and ''[[La traviata]]'' (with [[Antonietta Stella]] and [[Tito Gobbi]], 1955).\n\nFor English [[Decca Records|Decca]] he recorded ''[[L'elisir d'amore]]'' with [[Hilde Gueden]] and [[Fernando Corena]] (1955), ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'' (with [[Zinka Milanov]] and [[Leonard Warren]], 1957), ''[[La forza del destino]]'' (1958) and ''[[Tosca]]'' (with [[Leontyne Price]] and [[Giuseppe Taddei]], [[Herbert von Karajan]] conducting, 1962).\n\nFor [[Casa Ricordi|Ricordi]] (Ricordi MRO 104/105), he made a complete stereo ''Lucia di Lammermoor'' with [[Renata Scotto]], [[Ettore Bastianini]] and [[Ivo Vinco]] in 1958, with [[Nino Sanzogno]] conducting the Orchestra and Chorus of [[La Scala]], Milan.\n\nIn 1995, VAI issued an approved version of ''La boh\u00e8me'', from a 1959 performance in [[New Orleans]], with the tenor starring opposite [[Licia Albanese]], [[Audrey Schuh]], [[Giuseppe Valdengo]] and [[Norman Treigle]]. Additionally, in 1962 the tenor recorded excerpts from [[Jules Massenet|Massenet]]'s ''Manon'', with [[Anna Moffo]], conducted by [[Ren\u00e9 Leibowitz]].\n\nIn 1951, Di Stefano sang in a performance of Verdi's ''[[Requiem (Verdi)|Requiem]]'', at [[Carnegie Hall]], conducted by [[Arturo Toscanini]], the other soloists being [[Herva Nelli]], [[Fedora Barbieri]] and [[Cesare Siepi]]. It was released as a recording by [[RCA]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*''The Oxford Dictionary of Opera'', by [[John Warrack]] and Ewan West (1992), 782 pages, {{ISBN|0-19-869164-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Giuseppe Di Stefano}}\n* [http://www.operavivra.com/artists/tenors/di-stefano-giuseppe/ Extended biography at Opera Vivr\u00e0]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303223203/http://www.giuseppedistefano.it/indexeng.asp Official site] (mostly in Italian)\n* {{IMDb name|0224339}}\n* {{Find a Grave|25177173}}\n* [[Alan Blyth]] [http://music.guardian.co.uk/classical/comment/story/0,,2261837,00.html Obituary: Opera singer Giuseppe Di Stefano, 1921\u20132008] ''The Guardian'', 3 March 2008\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110831101318/http://historyofthetenor.com/page.php?90 History of the Tenor \u2013 Sound Clips and Narration]\n*{{YouTube|D5FI7IO1u4A|1974 concert with Maria Callas}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Stefano, Giuseppe}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian operatic tenors]]\n[[Category:Italian-language singers]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Catania]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian opera singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n", "nam